│ THOUGHT                                                                                                                      │
│ My previous attempt to fix the issue was unsuccessful. The crash remains the same, indicating my change did not address the  │
│ root cause. I need to re-analyze the problem.                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The core issue is that a `getelementptr` instruction (`%p.4`) is being incorrectly classified as "scalar" when it should be  │
│ "widened" (vectorized). This GEP is used by a `load` instruction that will be vectorized, and it's also used outside the     │
│ loop as a return value. The use outside the loop seems to be what's confusing the cost model into thinking the GEP should be │
│ scalar.                                                                                                                      │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ My previous fix attempted to modify the logic in `collectLoopScalars` to ignore uses outside the loop. This was incorrect    │
│ because that logic propagates scalar properties backwards from users to operands. The GEP itself is the one that needs to be │
│ classified correctly first.                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The decision to widen or scalarize happens in `VPRecipeBuilder::tryToCreateWidenRecipe`, which calls                         │
│ `VPRecipeBuilder::shouldWiden`. `shouldWiden` in turn calls `LoopVectorizationCostModel::isScalarAfterVectorization`. This   │
│ function is the key. It returns `true` if an instruction is in the `Scalars` set for the current vectorization factor.       │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The `Scalars` set is populated in `collectLoopScalars`. I need to find how `%p.4` gets into this set.                        │
│ After re-examining `collectLoopScalars`, I've found a different worklist expansion loop that seems to be the culprit:        │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ ```cpp                                                                                                                       │
│ // In LoopVectorize.cpp, inside collectLoopScalars                                                                           │
│ unsigned Idx = 0;                                                                                                            │
│ while (Idx != Worklist.size()) {                                                                                             │
│   Instruction *Dst = Worklist[Idx++];                                                                                        │
│   if (!IsLoopVaryingGEP(Dst->getOperand(0)))                                                                                 │
│     continue;                                                                                                                │
│   auto *Src = cast<Instruction>(Dst->getOperand(0));                                                                         │
│   if (llvm::all_of(Src->users(), [&](User *U) -> bool {                                                                      │
│         auto *J = cast<Instruction>(U);                                                                                      │
│         return !TheLoop->contains(J) || Worklist.count(J) ||                                                                 │
│                ((isa<LoadInst>(J) || isa<StoreInst>(J)) &&                                                                   │
│                 IsScalarUse(J, Src));                                                                                        │
│       })) {                                                                                                                  │
│     Worklist.insert(Src);                                                                                                    │
│   }                                                                                                                          │
│ }                                                                                                                            │
│ ```                                                                                                                          │
│ This loop propagates the scalar property from an instruction `Dst` to its operand `Src`. The condition                       │
│ `!TheLoop->contains(J)` allows a user outside the loop to be considered "scalar", which contributes to the `all_of` being    │
│ true. If an instruction's only non-scalar use is outside the loop, this logic will incorrectly classify it as scalar.        │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ This is exactly the case for the GEP `%p.4`. Its user `ret` is outside the loop. Its other user, the `load`, is vectorized,  │
│ so `IsScalarUse` is false for it. However, if the analysis starts from a different point and `%p.4`'s operand (`%ptr.iv`) is │
│ being considered, the logic can fail.                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The most direct way to fix this is to prevent the use outside the loop from influencing the decision. I will remove the      │
│ `!TheLoop->contains(J) ||` part of the condition. This forces the decision to be based only on in-loop users. If an          │
│ instruction has a vector use inside the loop, it will not be marked as scalar, which is the correct behavior. The live-out   │
│ value for the external user will be correctly extracted from the vectorized value later.                                     │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ This is the same reasoning as my previous attempt, but I believe I targeted the wrong loop. There are multiple similar       │
│ worklist expansion loops. The one at line 3175 is the one that seems to apply to GEP operands.                               │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                      │
│ sed -i '3177s/!TheLoop->contains(J) || //' llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp                                   │
│ ```                                                                                                                          │
